 or give any succour to those who wish to view the present (and the future) through the lens of fantasies about the transformative possibilities offered by conventional politics Butler demonstrates a clear engagement with an aspect of the world that is becoming in many political contexts almost illicit to discuss: the idea that capitalism, certainly in its neoliberal form, is failing to provide a liveable life for the majority of human beings.” —Mary Evans, Times Higher Education “A heady immersion into the thought of one of today’s most profound philosophers of action…This is a call for a truly transformative politics, and its relevance to the fraught struggles taking place in today’s streets and public spaces around the world cannot be denied.” —Hans Rollman, PopMatters  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aAssembly, Right ofxSocial aspects. 0aDemonstrations. 0aPerformative (Philosophy). 0aPublic meetings. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Political.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHarvard University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311066590140uhttps://doi.org/10.4159/978067449554840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780674495548423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780674495548.jpg  a978-3-11-066590-1  Harvard University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aGBV-deGruyter-alles